The tool was developed in the project COMPLETE - Completing management options in the Baltic Sea region to reduce risk of invasive species introduction by shipping [#R069] (https://www.balticcomplete.com/).

The tool is an influence diagram (ID) model, more specific a Bayesian network (BN) model and can be opened with a BN software that supports utility and decision nodes (see softwares available: https://www.cs.ubc.ca/~murphyk/Software/bnsoft.html).
The tool is developed using the software Hugin (https://www.hugin.com/) and this manual offers instructions for conducting the analyses with that software.

Benchmark Instances The proposed RHGA is tested on all the TSP instances with the number of cities ranging from 1,000 to 85,900 cities, with a total of 138, in the well-known and widely used benchmark sets for the TSP: TSPLIB (http://comopt.i.uni-heidelberg.de/software/TSPLIB95), National TSP benchmarks (http://www.math.uwaterloo.ca/tsp/world/countries.html) and VLSI TSP benchmarks (http://www.math.uwaterloo.ca/tsp/vlsi/index.html).

Baseline Algorithms For baseline algorithms in the comparison, we choose the EAX-GA with the default parameters (i.e., Npop= 300,Nch= 30), so-called EAX-300, the EAX-GA with larger population size (i.e., Npop= 400,Nch= 30), so-called EAX-400, and the current version of LKH (http://akira.ruc.dk/%7Ekeld/research/LKH/) in all the 138 benchmarks.
